Touched objects exploration

Luise Rauer

30 6 2022

Study design recommendations

  • Randomise samples of different time points to avoid batch effects
  • Include some comparable samples in each batch, in the best case positive controls
  • Additional advice for handling low-biomass samples by microbiology group (e.g.add qPCR data)

Summary of DADA2 recommendations

  • DADA2 truncLen: cutting has to leave enough overlap for merging forward and reverse reads (>20 bp). V3-V4 16S region has an expected length of 426 bp, so cutting at 200 & 200 leaves no overlap for merging
  • Also: unusual to cut forward and reverse reads symmetrically, usually forward reads are kept longer than reverse reads
  • DADA2 maxEE could be increased from default = 2 in QIIME2 to recover more reads
  • Cutting primers with cutadapt before using DADA2 might potentially lead to problems, because cutadapt does usually not remove primers in every sequence (as low as 70% in some samples here). This leads to different lengths per sequence and mis-aligns the bases per cycle, but this alignment in a prerequisite for the DADA2 error model.
  • Sequences in FASTQ file have two additional bases before the primer sequence (as stated in QIIME2 script)?

Sample processing

Based on https://benjjneb.github.io/dada2/tutorial.html.

Set DADA2 parameters

Calculating overlap for DADA2 truncLen parameters:

  • E. coli primer positions of V3V4 16S region: 341-357 forward (17 bp), 785-803 reverse (19 bp)
  • Sequencing: 2x300 bp (incl.primers), or 2x296 (sequence length in FASTQ files)
  • Expected amplicon length with primers: last pos. rev. primer - first pos. forw. primer = 803-341 = 462
  • Expected amplicon length without primers = 426
  • Overlap without truncation: Sequencing length forw. + sequencing length rev. - exp. amplicon length with primers = 300+300-462 = 138 bp overlap
  • Overlap for merging with current truncation settings: truncLen forw. + truncLen rev. - exp. amplicon length with primers = 280+250-462 = 68 bp overlap
  • (200+200-462 = -62 bp overlap)
# Set input directory
path <- "C:/Users/rauerlui/PhD/Sonstiges/2022.05 Museum touched objects microbiome/"
# Path of input FASTQ files
path_input <- paste0(path, "FASTQ/")
# Path for output
path_output <- paste0(path, "Output/")
# Set pattern for distinguishing forward and reverse FASTQ file names
forward_pattern <- "_R1.fastq.gz"
reverse_pattern <- "_R2.fastq.gz"

# Remove primers (forward: CCTACGGGWGGCWGCAG, reverse: CTACCRGGGTATCTAATCC)
trimLeft_par <- c(17, 19)
# Set cutting parameters & leave enough overlap for merging (> 20 bp).
truncLen_par <- c(280, 250)
# Additional parameters 
truncQ_par <- c(2, 2) 
maxEE_par <- c(2, 2) 
maxLen_par <- c(Inf, Inf) 
minLen_par <- c(20, 20) 
rm.phix_par <- TRUE

# Forward and reverse fastq filenames 
fnFs <- sort(list.files(path_input, pattern = forward_pattern, 
                        full.names = TRUE, recursive = TRUE))
fnRs <- sort(list.files(path_input, pattern = reverse_pattern, 
                        full.names = TRUE, recursive = TRUE))
# Extract sample names
sample.names <- gsub(forward_pattern, "", basename(fnFs))

Inspecting read quality

Interpretation:

  • Grey-scale background: heatmap of each quality score at each base position
  • Green line: mean quality score at each position
  • Orange line: quartiles of the quality score distribution
  • Red line: proportion of reads that extend to at least that position (not appearing if all sequences are equally long)
  • Blue line: current settings for cutting sequences
# Quality profiles for forward reads
plotQualityProfile(fnFs[c(1:10, 66:75)]) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = trimLeft_par[1]), colour = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = truncLen_par[1]), colour = "blue", alpha = 0.5)
## Warning: `guides(<scale> = FALSE)` is deprecated. Please use `guides(<scale> =

# Quality profiles for reverse reads

Quality filtering

# Create names for filtered files and for a subdirectory of your output folder
filtFs <- file.path(path_output, "filtered", 
                    paste0(sample.names, "_F_filt.fastq.gz"))
filtRs <- file.path(path_output, "filtered", 
                    paste0(sample.names, "_R_filt.fastq.gz"))
names(filtFs) <- sample.names
names(filtRs) <- sample.names

# Quality filtering
out <- filterAndTrim(fwd = fnFs, filt = filtFs, rev = fnRs, filt.rev = filtRs, 
                     truncLen = truncLen_par, trimLeft = trimLeft_par,
                     truncQ = truncQ_par, maxEE = maxEE_par, 
                     maxLen = maxLen_par, minLen = minLen_par, 
                     rm.phix = rm.phix_par, multithread = FALSE, 
                     verbose = FALSE)

Sample inference, merging & chimera removal

# Sample inference
dadaFs <- dada(filtFs[file.exists(filtFs)], err = errF, multithread = FALSE,
               verbose = FALSE)
dadaRs <- dada(filtRs[file.exists(filtRs)], err = errR, multithread = FALSE,
               verbose = FALSE)

# Merge forward and reverse reads
mergers <- mergePairs(
  dadaFs, filtFs[file.exists(filtFs)], dadaRs, filtRs[file.exists(filtRs)],
  verbose = FALSE)

# Construct a sequence table for all merged reads
seqtab <- makeSequenceTable(mergers)

# Chimera removal
seqtab.nochim <- removeBimeraDenovo(seqtab, method = "consensus", 
                                    multithread = TRUE, verbose = TRUE)
## Identified 1664 bimeras out of 8356 input sequences.

Sanity checks

# Number of samples & Number of ASVs
dim(seqtab.nochim) 
## [1]  126 6692
# Track reads through the pipeline (here a little advanced version that works
#   even if no reads in a sample pass the filter criteria)
getN <- function(x) sum(getUniques(x))
track <- list(data.frame(out, row.names = sample.names), 
              data.frame(sapply(dadaFs, getN)), 
              data.frame(sapply(dadaRs, getN)), 
              data.frame(sapply(mergers, getN)), 
              data.frame(rowSums(seqtab.nochim)))
track <- lapply(track, function(x) rownames_to_column(x, "sample"))
track <- track %>% purrr::reduce(merge, by = "sample", all = TRUE)
track <- track %>% column_to_rownames(var = "sample")
colnames(track) <- c("input", "filtered", "denoisedF", "denoisedR", "merged", 
                     "nonchim")
# Mean percentage of recovered reads per step
round(colMeans(track/track$input*100, na.rm = TRUE), 1)
##     input  filtered denoisedF denoisedR    merged   nonchim 
##     100.0      49.6      48.4      47.7      46.2      45.6
# Create an ASV table for filtering steps
seqtab.filt <- seqtab.nochim
# Plot distribution of sequence lengths
hist(nchar(getSequences(seqtab.nochim)))

Using new idtaxa

# Download trained clasifiers from: http://www2.decipher.codes/Downloads.html 
# Create a DNAStringSet from the ASVs
dna <- DNAStringSet(getSequences(seqtab.filt)) 
# Silva
load(paste0(path_output, "SILVA_SSU_r138_2019.RData"), verbose = TRUE) 
Sys.time() # takes ~ 35min
ids_silva <- IdTaxa(dna, trainingSet, strand = "top", processors = NULL, 
                    verbose = FALSE)
Sys.time()
ranks <- c("domain", "phylum", "class", "order", "family", "genus", "species") 
# Convert the output object of class "Taxa" to a matrix (like assignTaxonomy)
taxid_silva <- t(sapply(ids_silva, function(x) {
  m <- match(ranks, x$rank)
  taxa <- x$taxon[m]
  taxa[startsWith(taxa, "unclassified_")] <- NA
  taxa
}))
colnames(taxid_silva) <- ranks; rownames(taxid_silva) <- getSequences(seqtab.filt)

# RDP
load(paste0(path_output, "RDP_v18-mod_July2020.RData"), verbose = TRUE)

                    verbose = FALSE)
